---
import LegalLayout from '../../../layouts/LegalLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../../data/site';
import { articleSchema, faqPageSchema, breadcrumbSchema } from '../../../lib/seo/schema';

const updated = '2026-06-29';
const pageUrl = '/learn/how-to-read-eob/';
const canonical = new URL(pageUrl, site.url).href;
const title = 'How to Read an EOB (Explanation of Benefits)';
const description =
  'Plain-English guide to reading your insurance Explanation of Benefits — allowed amounts, patient responsibility, denial codes, and when to call your insurer.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is an EOB the same as a medical bill?',
    answer:
      'No. An EOB is a statement from your health insurer showing how a claim was processed. A bill is a request for payment from the provider. You may receive both for the same visit, and the amounts should eventually align.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why is the allowed amount lower than what the doctor billed?',
    answer:
      'For in-network care, your plan negotiates contracted rates with providers. The allowed amount is what the plan recognizes as payable. The difference between billed and allowed is often a contractual write-off, not something you owe.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What are CARC and RARC codes on an EOB?',
    answer:
      'CARC (Claim Adjustment Reason Codes) explain why a line was adjusted or denied. RARC (Remittance Advice Remark Codes) add short notes. Together they help you understand whether a denial is about network status, prior authorization, bundling, or another reason you may be able to appeal.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I pay the provider before I get my EOB?',
    answer:
      'Many people wait until both the EOB and provider bill arrive so they can compare patient responsibility. If you already paid and the EOB later shows a lower amount owed, you may be due a refund from the provider.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between an EOB and a Medicare Summary Notice?',
    answer:
      'Traditional Medicare sends a Medicare Summary Notice (MSN) instead of a commercial-style EOB. The MSN summarizes Part A and Part B claims processed by Medicare. Medicare Advantage plans send their own EOB-style statements from the private insurer.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I call my insurance company about an EOB?',
    answer:
      'Call when a line is denied and you do not understand why, when patient responsibility seems wrong given your deductible status, when out-of-network charges surprise you, or when the EOB does not match the provider bill after a reasonable wait. Have the claim number ready.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I use a tool to help read my EOB?',
    answer:
      'Yes. PatientBillGuide\'s free EOB Analyzer runs in your browser and helps organize pasted EOB text by line item. Pair it with our Fair Price Calculator to compare allowed amounts against Medicare benchmarks.',
  },
];

const schemaGraph = [
  articleSchema({
    headline: title,
    description,
    url: canonical,
    dateModified: updated,
    authorName: 'Vigen',
    authorUrl: `${site.url}/authors/vigen/`,
  }),
  faqPageSchema(faqs),
  breadcrumbSchema(
    [
      { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
      { name: 'Learn', url: '/learn/' },
      { name: 'How to Read an EOB' },
    ],
    site.url,
  ),
];
---

<LegalLayout title={title} description={description} crumbs={[{ label: 'Learn', href: '/learn/' }, { label: 'How to Read an EOB' }]}>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schemaGraph)} />
  </Fragment>

  <p class="article-byline">
    Written by <a href="/authors/vigen/">Vigen</a> · Last updated {updated}
  </p>

  <nav class="article-toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
    <h2>On this page</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="#what-is-eob">What is an EOB?</a></li>
      <li><a href="#eob-vs-bill">EOB vs. medical bill</a></li>
      <li><a href="#key-columns">Key columns on your EOB</a></li>
      <li><a href="#deductibles-oop">Deductibles and out-of-pocket max</a></li>
      <li><a href="#denial-codes">Denial and adjustment codes (CARC/RARC)</a></li>
      <li><a href="#network-status">In-network vs. out-of-network</a></li>
      <li><a href="#hospital-bills">Coordinating with hospital bills</a></li>
      <li><a href="#call-insurer">When to call your insurer</a></li>
      <li><a href="#medicare-msn">Medicare and the MSN</a></li>
      <li><a href="#workflow">Step-by-step workflow</a></li>
      <li><a href="#tools">Tools that can help</a></li>
      <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <h2 id="what-is-eob">What is an EOB?</h2>
  <p>
    An <strong>Explanation of Benefits (EOB)</strong> is a statement your health insurance company sends
    after it processes a medical claim. It summarizes what the provider billed, what your plan allowed,
    what insurance paid, and what you may still owe. Despite the name, an EOB is <em>not</em> a bill — you
    do not send payment to your insurer based on the EOB alone.
  </p>
  <p>
    Think of the EOB as your insurer's receipt for the claim. It shows how your plan applied your
    benefits: deductible, copayments, coinsurance, and any amounts the plan does not cover. Every insured
    person with private coverage (employer plan, marketplace plan, or individual policy) receives EOBs
    for most medical services, though the layout varies by company.
  </p>
  <p>
    EOBs usually arrive by mail or through your insurer's online portal, often days or weeks after the
    visit. That delay is normal. Claims move from the provider's billing office to a clearinghouse, then
    to your insurer, where they are priced, checked against your benefits, and either paid or adjusted.
    Understanding the EOB helps you confirm you were charged correctly before you pay a provider bill.
  </p>

  <h2 id="eob-vs-bill">EOB vs. medical bill</h2>
  <p>
    After a doctor visit, imaging test, or hospital stay, you may receive <strong>two different
    documents</strong>: an EOB from your insurer and a bill from the hospital or physician group. They
    describe the same care from different perspectives. The provider bill asks you to pay; the EOB
    explains how insurance handled the underlying claim.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <strong>patient responsibility</strong> on the EOB should match what the provider eventually
    bills you, though timing rarely lines up perfectly. Providers often send a bill before insurance
    finishes processing, which can show a higher "balance due" that later drops once the EOB is final. If
    you receive a bill that does not match your EOB's patient responsibility after both are final, that
    mismatch is worth a phone call — first to the provider's billing department, then to your insurer if
    needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you paid the provider upfront or paid more than the EOB later shows you owe, you may be entitled
    to a refund. Keep EOBs, bills, and payment receipts together until the account is settled. For a
    deeper look at hospital statements, see our guide on <a href="/learn/how-to-read-medical-bill/">how to
    read a medical bill</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="key-columns">Key columns on your EOB</h2>
  <p>
    Layouts differ, but most EOBs repeat the same financial building blocks for each line of service.
    Learning these columns makes every EOB easier to read.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Date of service</strong> — when the visit, test, or procedure occurred. Match this to your
      calendar and any after-visit summary.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Provider or facility name</strong> — who performed the service. Hospital stays may list
      multiple providers (emergency physician, radiologist, pathologist) on separate lines.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Procedure or service code</strong> — often a five-digit <a href="/learn/cpt-codes-explained/">CPT
      code</a> or HCPCS code describing what was done. This code drives how the claim is priced.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Billed amount</strong> — the charge the provider submitted. This is frequently higher than
      what insurance recognizes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Allowed amount</strong> — the price your plan accepts for that service after network
      contracts or plan rules. For in-network care, the difference between billed and allowed is usually
      not your responsibility.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan paid</strong> — what your insurer paid the provider (or what it will pay). This may be
      zero if you have not met your deductible or if the service is not covered.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Patient responsibility</strong> — the portion assigned to you: deductible, copay,
      coinsurance, or non-covered charges. This is the number to compare to your provider bill.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Remark or reason codes</strong> — short codes explaining adjustments. See the CARC/RARC
      section below.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some EOBs also show <strong>claim number</strong>, <strong>group or member ID</strong>, and
    year-to-date totals for deductible and out-of-pocket spending. Note the claim number — you will need
    it when calling customer service.
  </p>

  <h2 id="deductibles-oop">Deductibles and out-of-pocket max</h2>
  <p>
    Your EOB applies each charge against your plan's cost-sharing rules. Three concepts appear on almost
    every statement:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Deductible</strong> — the amount you pay for covered services before insurance starts paying
      its share (except for services your plan covers with a copay before the deductible is met). EOBs
      often show "deductible remaining" for the plan year.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Copay</strong> — a flat fee for certain visits or prescriptions, defined in your plan
      documents.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Coinsurance</strong> — a percentage of the allowed amount you pay after the deductible is
      met (for example, you pay 20% and the plan pays 80%).
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The <strong>out-of-pocket maximum (OOP max)</strong> caps what you pay in deductibles, copays, and
    coinsurance for covered in-network care in a plan year. After you hit the OOP max, your plan typically
    pays 100% of allowed amounts for covered services. Premiums do not count toward the OOP max. Neither
    do charges for out-of-network care or services your plan excludes.
  </p>
  <p>
    When reading an EOB, check whether a line applied to your deductible or was subject to coinsurance.
    If you believed you had already met your deductible but the EOB shows otherwise, compare the
    year-to-date totals on recent EOBs or your insurer's online account. Errors in deductible tracking
    do happen and can often be corrected with a call.
  </p>

  <h2 id="denial-codes">Denial and adjustment codes (CARC/RARC)</h2>
  <p>
    When a line is reduced or denied, the EOB usually includes standardized codes. The most common are
    <strong>CARC</strong> (Claim Adjustment Reason Codes) and <strong>RARC</strong> (Remittance Advice
    Remark Codes). Insurers and providers use these nationwide, so the same code on your Anthem EOB may
    appear on a friend's UnitedHealthcare statement.
  </p>
  <p>
    A <strong>CARC</strong> explains <em>why</em> money moved — for example, "contractual obligation"
    (the provider agreed to accept less than billed), "deductible amount," or "not covered by plan." A
    <strong>RARC</strong> adds a plain-language remark, such as a reminder that prior authorization was
    required. You do not need to memorize every code. Instead, look up the code on your insurer's website
    or ask customer service what it means for your specific claim.
  </p>
  <p>
    Common adjustment reasons patients encounter include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Out-of-network</strong> — the provider does not have a contract with your plan, so allowed
      amounts and patient responsibility may be much higher.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Prior authorization not obtained</strong> — some plans require approval before imaging,
      surgery, or certain drugs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bundled or inclusive</strong> — a service was considered part of another procedure and not
      paid separately.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Duplicate claim</strong> — the same service was billed twice.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Non-covered benefit</strong> — the service is excluded by your plan (cosmetic procedures,
      for example).
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many denials can be <strong>appealed</strong> if you have documentation — a letter of medical necessity
    from your doctor, proof that authorization was requested, or evidence that the service was
    emergency care. Appeals have deadlines, often 180 days from the EOB date. PatientBillGuide does not
    provide legal advice, but understanding the code on your EOB is the first step toward a productive
    conversation with your insurer.
  </p>

  <h2 id="network-status">In-network vs. out-of-network</h2>
  <p>
    Network status is one of the biggest drivers of what your EOB shows. <strong>In-network</strong>
    providers have contracts with your plan. They agree to discounted rates, and your plan limits your
    cost-sharing to copays, deductible, and coinsurance defined in your policy. The EOB's allowed amount
    reflects that contracted rate.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Out-of-network</strong> providers do not have that contract (or the claim was processed as
    out-of-network because of a paperwork issue). Your plan may pay a smaller portion — or nothing — and
    the provider may bill you for the difference between billed and allowed, a practice called balance
    billing in many states. Surprise bills from out-of-network clinicians at in-network hospitals have
    received federal and state consumer protections in recent years, but rules vary. If your EOB flags
    out-of-network charges for care you believed was in-network, ask both the provider and insurer to
    explain.
  </p>
  <p>
  To check whether a charge is reasonable even when out-of-network, compare the allowed amount to
  <a href="/tools/fair-price/">Medicare benchmarks</a> for the same <a href="/codes/">CPT code</a> in
  your area. Medicare rates are not what private insurers pay, but they provide a documented public
  reference point when you are negotiating or appealing.
  </p>

  <h2 id="hospital-bills">Coordinating with hospital bills</h2>
  <p>
    Hospital care is especially confusing because you may receive <strong>many EOBs and bills</strong> for
    one stay: the hospital facility fee, emergency physician, anesthesiologist, radiology, lab work, and
    follow-up visits. Each entity bills separately. Your insurer sends a separate EOB (or EOB section) per
    claim.
  </p>
  <p>
    Work through hospital paperwork systematically:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Gather every EOB and every provider bill for the same date range.
    </li>
    <li>
      Sort by date of service and match CPT codes across documents.
    </li>
    <li>
      Confirm each EOB line has a corresponding bill (or that the provider is still waiting to bill you).
    </li>
    <li>
      Add up patient responsibility only once per service — do not pay the same line on both a
      preliminary bill and a revised bill without checking.
    </li>
    <li>
      Watch for <strong>facility fees</strong> vs. <strong>professional fees</strong> for the same
      encounter. Our <a href="/learn/how-to-read-medical-bill/">medical bill guide</a> explains this
      split in detail.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Hospital bills sometimes arrive before insurance processing finishes. If a bill says "insurance
    pending," wait for the EOB before paying the patient portion. If a bill demands immediate payment
    while insurance is still processing, call the hospital billing office and ask them to hold the
    account until the claim is final.
  </p>

  <h2 id="call-insurer">When to call your insurer</h2>
  <p>
    Not every EOB requires a phone call. If patient responsibility matches your expectations and aligns
    with the provider bill, you can usually pay and file the paperwork. Call your insurer when:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A service you believed was covered is denied or marked non-covered.</li>
    <li>Out-of-network charges appear for an in-network hospital or office visit.</li>
    <li>Patient responsibility does not match your deductible or OOP max status.</li>
    <li>The same claim was processed twice or totals look duplicated.</li>
    <li>You need help interpreting a CARC/RARC code or starting an appeal.</li>
    <li>The provider bill and final EOB still disagree after both sides have had time to process.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before you call, have your <strong>member ID</strong>, <strong>claim number</strong>, date of
    service, provider name, and CPT code ready. Take notes on the representative's name, date, and what
    they promised. Many insurers can reprocess a claim if the provider submits corrected information.
  </p>

  <h2 id="medicare-msn">Medicare and the MSN</h2>
  <p>
    If you have <strong>Original Medicare</strong> (Part A and Part B), you will not receive a commercial
    EOB. Instead, Medicare mails a <strong>Medicare Summary Notice (MSN)</strong> every three months
    listing claims processed during that period. You can also view claims anytime at Medicare.gov. The MSN
    shows what Medicare approved, what it paid, and the maximum you may owe providers.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Medicare Advantage</strong> (Part C) plans are run by private insurers. Those plans send
    EOB-style statements that look like employer coverage. <strong>Medigap</strong> and retiree
    supplemental plans send their own notices after Medicare pays. If you have several types of coverage,
    you may need to cross-reference multiple documents for one procedure.
  </p>
  <p>
    Key MSN columns parallel commercial EOBs: billed amount, Medicare-approved amount, amount Medicare
    paid, and maximum you may be billed. Providers who accept Medicare assignment agree not to charge
    more than the approved amount (except coinsurance and deductible). See our <a
    href="/for/seniors-medicare/">Medicare audience guide</a> for more context.
  </p>

  <h2 id="workflow">Step-by-step workflow</h2>
  <p>
    Use this workflow each time you receive an EOB for care you want to verify:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Confirm identity.</strong> Check member name, date of service, and provider. Report
      unfamiliar claims immediately — they could be a billing error or identity issue.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Match the visit.</strong> Did you actually receive the service on that date? Typos in dates
      or wrong-patient claims do occur.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read each line's codes.</strong> Look up unfamiliar <a href="/codes/">CPT codes</a> in our
      encyclopedia or glossary.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Compare billed vs. allowed.</strong> For in-network care, verify the large billed amount
      was mostly written off and your share is based on the allowed amount.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Check deductible and OOP totals.</strong> Does this EOB fit your year-to-date progress?
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Note denials and codes.</strong> Write down CARC/RARC codes and deadlines for appeals.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Wait for the provider bill</strong> (or pull it from the portal) and compare patient
      responsibility.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pay, appeal, or call</strong> — pay if amounts align; appeal or call if they do not.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>File paperwork</strong> — keep the EOB with the paid bill for tax or HSA records.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    For a faster first pass, paste EOB text into our <a href="/tools/eob-analyzer/">EOB Analyzer</a>.
    It runs locally in your browser and organizes line items so you can spot outliers before you call
    anyone.
  </p>

  <h2 id="tools">Tools that can help</h2>
  <p>
    PatientBillGuide offers free, browser-based tools that complement this guide:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="/tools/eob-analyzer/"><strong>EOB Analyzer</strong></a> — paste EOB text to summarize
      line items, codes, and amounts. Nothing is uploaded to our servers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/tools/fair-price/"><strong>Fair Price Calculator</strong></a> — enter a CPT code and ZIP
      code to see Medicare allowed amounts and a documented fair range for comparison.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/codes/"><strong>CPT code encyclopedia</strong></a> — plain-English guides to common
      procedure codes with typical cost context.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/learn/how-to-read-medical-bill/"><strong>How to read a medical bill</strong></a> — for
      when the hospital or clinic statement arrives.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These tools support your review; they do not replace conversations with your insurer or provider when
    something looks wrong. See our <a href="/methodology/limitations/">methodology limitations</a> for
    what benchmarks can and cannot tell you.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
  <dl class="faq">
    {
      faqs.map((item) => (
        <>
          <dt>{item.question}</dt>
          <dd>{item.answer}</dd>
        </>
      ))
    }
  </dl>
</LegalLayout>
